    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1888-05-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1888-05-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="498" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d498">
                <head>No. 43.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName> to Sir <persName type="to">L. S. Sackville
                                    West</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1888-05-29">
                            <hi rend="italic">May</hi> 29,
                                1888</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">Personal.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Sir Lionel</hi>: I have just sent you a reply
                            to your, notes (official) of April 30 and May 25 relating to appeals in
                            the cases of seizure in Behring Sea.</p>
                <p>I have this moment received your note of today inclosing a memorandum to
                            the effect that by reason of the failure of the proctors of the <pb facs="0850" n="1808" xml:id="pg_1808"/> vessels so seized, no
                            appeals from the decrees of condemnation have been entered, and the time
                            fixed by law for doing so having expired, none other than relief through
                            diplomatic channels remains.</p>
                <p>It is much to be regretted that the order of the Attorney-General
                            respecting acceptance of security and release of these vessels had not
                            been availed of by these parties. I will, however, write at once to my
                            colleague, the Attorney-General, and see what remains to be done in his
                            Department.</p>
                <p>Very truly, yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">T. F. Bayard.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
